title: ExpressiveTyping: A new way to sense keyboard preessure with embedded accelerometer
title_en: ExpressiveTyping: A new way to sense keyboard preessure with embedded accelerometer
abstract: 本研究はキーボードに埋め込んだ加速度計を用いてキー入力時の押圧を検知する新しい手法を提案している。日本語や英語のタイピングに圧力情報を導入することを通じて入力インターフェースの表現性を向上させ、既存の市販ノートPCに追加の圧力センサを必要とせずに押圧情報を取得する方法を示している。
abstract_en: This work proposes a novel method that senses keypress pressure using an accelerometer embedded in a keyboard. The method aims to enhance expressive input by capturing pressure information without requiring additional pressure sensors on commodity notebook PCs.
positioning_summary: 本研究は従来のタイピングが押圧情報を取得していないというギャップに着目して新しい押圧検知のアプローチを提案している。本文は追加センサを必要としない形で入力インターフェースの表現性を高めることを目標としてギャップを埋める位置づけを示している。
positioning_summary_en: This research positions itself by addressing the lack of pressure information in conventional typing and proposes a new approach for pressure sensing. The work is positioned to fill that gap by aiming to enhance input expressivity without requiring extra sensors.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的は市販のノートPC上で追加の圧力センサを用いずにキー押圧情報を取得してタイピングに圧力による表現性を付与することである。本文は押圧情報を取得することでテキスト入力の表現性とフィードバックの幅を広げることを具体的な目的としている。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this research is to acquire keypress pressure information on commodity notebook PCs without additional pressure sensors, thereby adding pressure-based expressivity to typing. The work specifically aims to broaden the expressive and feedback capabilities of text input by obtaining pressure signals.
method_summary: 本手法はキーボードに埋め込んだ加速度計のx/y/z成分を取得して押圧に対応する信号を抽出する方式を採用している。本文は200Hzでの加速度取得と高速度カメラによる200fpsのキーストローク計測を組み合わせて加速度信号と押圧やストローク速度との対応を解析する具体的な手法を提示している。
method_summary_en: The method acquires x/y/z components from an accelerometer embedded in a keyboard and extracts signals corresponding to keypress pressure. The approach combines 200 Hz accelerometer sampling with 200 fps high-speed camera keystroke measurements to analyze the relationship between accelerometer signals and pressure or stroke velocity.
evaluation_summary: 本評価は高速度カメラで計測したキーストローク速度と加速度計出力を比較する実験に基づいて実施された評価手法を用いている。本文は速度50.56 cm/sで加速度35.86 (Gx100)、30.48 cm/sで14.34 (Gx100)という対応を観察し、加速度計信号が押圧やストローク速度と相関することを示した。
evaluation_summary_en: The evaluation used experiments that compared keystroke velocities measured by a high-speed camera with outputs from the accelerometer to assess the method. The experiments observed correspondences such as 50.56 cm/s associated with 35.86 (Gx100) and 30.48 cm/s associated with 14.34 (Gx100), indicating that accelerometer signals correlate with pressure and stroke velocity.

Title: ExpressiveTyping: A new way to sense keyboard preessure with embedded accelerometer
Authors: Ken-ichiro Iwasaki, Takashi Miyaki, Jun Rekimoto
Year: 2008
Abstract: This work proposes a novel method that senses keypress pressure using an accelerometer embedded in a keyboard. The method aims to enhance expressive input by capturing pressure information without requiring additional pressure sensors on commodity notebook PCs.
Positioning Summary: This research positions itself by addressing the lack of pressure information in conventional typing and proposes a new approach for pressure sensing. The work is positioned to fill that gap by aiming to enhance input expressivity without requiring extra sensors.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this research is to acquire keypress pressure information on commodity notebook PCs without additional pressure sensors, thereby adding pressure-based expressivity to typing. The work specifically aims to broaden the expressive and feedback capabilities of text input by obtaining pressure signals.
Method Summary: The method acquires x/y/z components from an accelerometer embedded in a keyboard and extracts signals corresponding to keypress pressure. The approach combines 200 Hz accelerometer sampling with 200 fps high-speed camera keystroke measurements to analyze the relationship between accelerometer signals and pressure or stroke velocity.
Evaluation Summary: The evaluation used experiments that compared keystroke velocities measured by a high-speed camera with outputs from the accelerometer to assess the method. The experiments observed correspondences such as 50.56 cm/s associated with 35.86 (Gx100) and 30.48 cm/s associated with 14.34 (Gx100), indicating that accelerometer signals correlate with pressure and stroke velocity.
